It's quite impressive, and
thanks to the tech crew.

00:04:43.500 --> 00:04:46.050
So "Welcome to the Rock" was
the opening for that song.

00:04:46.050 --> 00:04:47.730
What is the rock?

00:04:47.730 --> 00:04:49.272
DAVID HEIN: The rock
is Newfoundland.

00:04:49.272 --> 00:04:50.063
ALAN SEALES: Right.

00:04:50.063 --> 00:04:52.115
DAVID HEIN: Newfoundland
is an island province

00:04:52.115 --> 00:04:55.660
on the Northeast tip of
North America, in Canada.

00:04:55.660 --> 00:05:00.840
And in 2001, they welcomed a
number of planes and passengers

00:05:00.840 --> 00:05:02.790
because all the planes
were diverted when

00:05:02.790 --> 00:05:04.050
the US airspace was closed.

00:05:04.050 --> 00:05:04.620
ALAN SEALES: Right, OK.

00:05:04.620 --> 00:05:06.786
So I want to get into the
timeline about this first.

00:05:06.786 --> 00:05:08.384
But the four of you
who just joined us

00:05:08.384 --> 00:05:10.800
after the performance, go down
the line here and introduce

00:05:10.800 --> 00:05:11.850
yourselves and what you do.

00:05:11.850 --> 00:05:13.100
DAVID HEIN: So I'm David Hein.

00:05:13.100 --> 00:05:14.200
I'm one of the writers.

00:05:14.200 --> 00:05:15.574
IRENE SANKOFF:
I'm Irene Sankoff.

00:05:15.574 --> 00:05:16.782
I am the other writer.

00:05:16.782 --> 00:05:18.240
IAN EISENDRATH:
I'm Ian Eisendrath.

00:05:18.240 --> 00:05:20.699
I'm the music supervisor,
arranger, and conductor.

00:05:20.699 --> 00:05:21.990
KELLY DEVINE: I'm Kelly Devine.

00:05:21.990 --> 00:05:23.372
I'm the choreographer.

00:05:23.372 --> 00:05:24.330
ALAN SEALES: Wonderful.

00:05:24.330 --> 00:05:28.880
OK, so the timeline of
September 11th, 9:26,

00:05:28.880 --> 00:05:30.090
FAA closes airspace.

00:05:30.090 --> 00:05:32.760
12:00 PM, 18 planes--

00:05:32.760 --> 00:05:35.030
Gander, the city
that this happens in,

00:05:35.030 --> 00:05:37.710
was told 18 planes will land.

00:05:37.710 --> 00:05:42.486
And then by 12:15, 13
additional planes had landed.

00:05:42.486 --> 00:05:43.860
And then at the
end of it all, it

00:05:43.860 --> 00:05:49.260
was 38 planes total, carrying
almost 7,000 people into--

00:05:49.260 --> 00:05:51.960
came into a town that only
had 10,000 people in it

00:05:51.960 --> 00:05:53.852
to begin with.

00:05:53.852 --> 00:05:56.310
And they weren't even allowed
to leave the plane for hours,

00:05:56.310 --> 00:05:56.550
right?

00:05:56.550 --> 00:05:57.360
DAVID HEIN: Yeah.

00:05:57.360 --> 00:05:59.540
ALAN SEALES: So
getting into that--

00:05:59.540 --> 00:06:03.580
as the writers, I think this
all begins with the two of you.

00:06:03.580 --> 00:06:05.350
Why?

00:06:05.350 --> 00:06:07.710
Where did you find this story,
and why did you write it?

00:06:08.680 --> 00:06:10.680
IRENE SANKOFF: It was a
story that was suggested

00:06:10.680 --> 00:06:12.580
to us by a friend of ours.

00:06:12.580 --> 00:06:14.920
And we applied to
get a grant to go out

00:06:14.920 --> 00:06:17.732
to see what was happening on the
10th anniversary of September

00:06:17.732 --> 00:06:20.190
11, because a lot of the people
who had been stranded there

00:06:20.190 --> 00:06:23.790
10 years before were going
to return because 10 years

00:06:23.790 --> 00:06:27.297
later, they still felt so
much gratitude and so much

00:06:27.297 --> 00:06:29.130
respect for the people
who had taken them in

00:06:29.130 --> 00:06:30.360
and had become lifelong friends.

00:06:30.360 --> 00:06:31.943
So we thought, OK,
there's going to be

00:06:31.943 --> 00:06:33.390
all these ceremonies happening.

00:06:33.390 --> 00:06:36.330
We need to be there
and just find out

00:06:36.330 --> 00:06:39.780
why this place means
so much to these people

00:06:39.780 --> 00:06:42.210
that they would come
back 10 years later.

00:06:42.210 --> 00:06:43.890
DAVID HEIN: So we
traveled out there.

00:06:43.890 --> 00:06:45.860
We, like Irene said,
we had a grant,

00:06:45.860 --> 00:06:48.432
but we actually got to stay a
little bit longer to extend it

00:06:48.432 --> 00:06:49.890
because the people
were there like,

00:06:49.890 --> 00:06:51.390
uh, don't spend
money on a hotel.

00:06:51.390 --> 00:06:52.140
Come stay with us.

00:06:52.140 --> 00:06:53.640
Here's the keys,
just feed the cats.

00:06:53.640 --> 00:06:56.010
ALAN SEALES: So they still
extended the hospitality

00:06:56.010 --> 00:06:56.552
all the time.

00:06:56.552 --> 00:06:58.843
DAVID HEIN: Yeah, we saw the
same generosity out there.

00:06:58.843 --> 00:07:00.390
And we ended up
interviewing everyone

00:07:00.390 --> 00:07:02.550
we possibly could
for hours at a time,

00:07:02.550 --> 00:07:03.900
and we just came back with--

00:07:03.900 --> 00:07:06.650
you mentioned 7,000
people on the plane,

00:07:06.650 --> 00:07:08.320
there was around
9,000 people in town.

00:07:08.320 --> 00:07:10.080
And we came back with
like 16,000 stories,

00:07:10.080 --> 00:07:11.490
and we wanted to
tell all of them

00:07:11.490 --> 00:07:15.159
and tried to do that in 100
minute musical with 12 actors.

00:07:15.159 --> 00:07:17.700
ALAN SEALES: Well, OK, so I want
to take a step back, though.

00:07:17.700 --> 00:07:20.280
The title, "Come From Away,"
what is a come from away?

00:07:20.280 --> 00:07:21.946
IRENE SANKOFF: Come
from away is someone

00:07:21.946 --> 00:07:24.010
who is not from Newfoundland.

00:07:24.010 --> 00:07:25.890
So if you're not
born on the rock,

00:07:25.890 --> 00:07:28.082
then you're considered
a come from away.

00:07:28.082 --> 00:07:29.790
ALAN SEALES: And is
it like a New Yorker,

00:07:29.790 --> 00:07:31.830
where after 10 years
and you get angry enough

00:07:31.830 --> 00:07:33.627
you become a New Yorker?

00:07:33.627 --> 00:07:34.960
IRENE SANKOFF: I don't think so.

00:07:34.960 --> 00:07:35.400
I don't think so.

00:07:35.400 --> 00:07:37.020
I think you could
have lived on a rock

00:07:37.020 --> 00:07:39.369
longer than if
you had actually--

00:07:39.369 --> 00:07:40.910
like than you've
lived anywhere else,

00:07:40.910 --> 00:07:43.140
and you're still come from away.

00:07:43.140 --> 00:07:46.092
Although apparently, David
and I are now honorary--

00:07:46.092 --> 00:07:47.550
DAVID HEIN: There's
a ceremony that

00:07:47.550 --> 00:07:49.216
happens in the show
called a screech in,

00:07:49.216 --> 00:07:52.590
where you ostensibly become
an honorary Newfoundlander,

00:07:52.590 --> 00:07:54.400
and that's happened
to us three times.

00:07:54.400 --> 00:07:56.300
You have to kiss a fish, you
have to drink some drinks.

00:07:56.300 --> 00:07:56.930
ALAN SEALES: But that's real?

00:07:56.930 --> 00:07:57.440
DAVID HEIN: It's real.

00:07:57.440 --> 00:07:57.790
IRENE SANKOFF: Oh yeah.

00:07:57.790 --> 00:07:58.280
ALAN SEALES: Oh wow.

00:07:58.280 --> 00:08:00.360
DAVID HEIN: So it's happened
to us three times and--

00:08:00.360 --> 00:08:01.818
ALAN SEALES: You
kissed three fish.

00:08:01.818 --> 00:08:02.670
DAVID HEIN: Yes.

00:08:02.670 --> 00:08:03.170
Yep.

00:08:03.170 --> 00:08:04.680
I mean, in the ceremony.

00:08:07.470 --> 00:08:09.600
But at the end of
that, we were talking

00:08:09.600 --> 00:08:11.933
to one of the Newfoundlanders
that we based the show on.

00:08:11.933 --> 00:08:14.370
And I would saying, so, we've
been screeched in already.

00:08:14.370 --> 00:08:15.420
We've been screeched
in three times.

00:08:15.420 --> 00:08:16.336
We're Newfoundlanders.

00:08:16.336 --> 00:08:19.080
He's like, no, you're
a mainlander still.

00:08:19.080 --> 00:08:23.080
I was like, we wrote
a show about you.

00:08:23.080 --> 00:08:25.710
ALAN SEALES: So
did the skeptics,

00:08:25.710 --> 00:08:28.147
I guess-- when you were
trying to put this together,

00:08:28.147 --> 00:08:29.730
were there are people
who were saying,

00:08:29.730 --> 00:08:32.760
like, you guys are
insane to make a musical,

00:08:32.760 --> 00:08:34.799
to write music or write
a story about this

00:08:34.799 --> 00:08:36.150
and try to get it on stage.

00:08:36.150 --> 00:08:38.405
I mean, was there
any adversity there?

00:08:38.405 --> 00:08:39.530
DAVID HEIN: Yeah, I think--

00:08:39.530 --> 00:08:40.360
IRENE SANKOFF: Oh, yeah.

00:08:40.360 --> 00:08:42.460
Yeah, I mean, like starting
writing Newfoundland

00:08:42.460 --> 00:08:45.001
and we were getting a tour of
the airport and the guy's like,

00:08:45.001 --> 00:08:46.590
so you're going
to write a musical

00:08:46.590 --> 00:08:49.200
about making people sandwiches?

00:08:49.200 --> 00:08:50.592
Good luck with that.

00:08:50.592 --> 00:08:52.050
DAVID HEIN: And
then beyond that, I

00:08:52.050 --> 00:08:55.380
mean obviously, it's set against
the backdrop of what happened

00:08:55.380 --> 00:08:56.680
here in New York on 9/11.

00:08:56.680 --> 00:09:00.300
And we've been very clear
that it's not a 9/11 story,

00:09:00.300 --> 00:09:01.390
it's a 9/12 story.

00:09:01.390 --> 00:09:04.234
It's about the way this
community responded to it.

00:09:04.234 --> 00:09:06.150
But also, we had a lot
of sensitivity to that.

00:09:06.150 --> 00:09:07.600
We were living here on 9/11.

00:09:07.600 --> 00:09:10.980
My cousin was in the towers,
but fortunately he got out.

00:09:10.980 --> 00:09:13.770
But there was a lot of what
happened in Newfoundland that

00:09:13.770 --> 00:09:16.170
resonated with us
in terms of-- we

00:09:16.170 --> 00:09:18.180
lived up at around
122nd and Broadway,

00:09:18.180 --> 00:09:20.501
at this residence for
international graduate

00:09:20.501 --> 00:09:21.000
students.

00:09:21.000 --> 00:09:23.970
So people from 110 countries
from around the world all

00:09:23.970 --> 00:09:26.610
waiting for news, all
waiting for them to return

00:09:26.610 --> 00:09:29.037
and supporting each
other as a community.

00:09:29.037 --> 00:09:31.620
So there's something about this
international community coming

00:09:31.620 --> 00:09:35.020
together to each other
that was familiar to us.

00:09:35.020 --> 00:09:38.040
But also in the time
after 9/11 in New York,

00:09:38.040 --> 00:09:39.660
it felt like there was--

00:09:39.660 --> 00:09:41.550
the boundaries broke
down between people.

00:09:41.550 --> 00:09:43.520
You could reach out to
anyone and say, you OK?

00:09:43.520 --> 00:09:44.280
How are you doing?

00:09:44.280 --> 00:09:46.530
And that's what happened
in Newfoundland.

00:09:46.530 --> 00:09:49.500
I think that's what happened
internationally in many cities.

00:09:49.500 --> 00:09:51.739
And it's something that--

00:09:51.739 --> 00:09:54.030
what happened in Newfoundland
reminded us of that time.

00:09:54.030 --> 00:09:56.071
It reminded us of how kind
we were to each other.

00:09:56.071 --> 00:09:58.344
And so there's something
that really resonated with us

00:09:58.344 --> 00:09:59.010
about the story.

00:09:59.010 --> 00:10:00.390
ALAN SEALES: It's interesting
that what you just said

00:10:00.390 --> 00:10:02.830
resonates with me, that
the boundaries went down.

00:10:02.830 --> 00:10:04.710
Again, like your
morning commute,

00:10:04.710 --> 00:10:06.150
going to and from work,
whatever, you're just like,

00:10:06.150 --> 00:10:07.620
don't touch me,
get out of my way,

00:10:07.620 --> 00:10:09.537
tourists pointing their
fingers in your faces.

00:10:09.537 --> 00:10:12.120
And then you've got a whole town
of people here that just say,

00:10:12.120 --> 00:10:13.860
screw it, let's let
all these people in.

00:10:13.860 --> 00:10:14.550
They have nowhere to go.

00:10:14.550 --> 00:10:16.050
They've been in
a plane for hours

00:10:16.050 --> 00:10:19.230
and don't know
when they will ever

00:10:19.230 --> 00:10:21.270
get back on, if they
will anytime soon.

00:10:21.270 --> 00:10:23.850
So yeah, it was a
nice story to tell.

00:10:23.850 --> 00:10:24.840
And then it went to--

00:10:24.840 --> 00:10:26.942
you did a run in Toronto, right?

00:10:26.942 --> 00:10:27.650
DAVID HEIN: Yeah.

00:10:27.650 --> 00:10:30.930
So it was originally
workshopped in Toronto.

00:10:30.930 --> 00:10:33.846
And then we took
it to Connecticut.

00:10:33.846 --> 00:10:34.970
We did a presentation here.

00:10:34.970 --> 00:10:35.860
ALAN SEALES:
Connecticut, really?

00:10:35.860 --> 00:10:37.620
DAVID HEIN: Yeah, at
Goodspeed festivals.

00:10:37.620 --> 00:10:40.440
And then we did the first
production with these guys,

00:10:40.440 --> 00:10:43.050
with almost all these
guys in San Diego, which

00:10:43.050 --> 00:10:45.810
was a co-production with
Seattle Rep, La Jolla

00:10:45.810 --> 00:10:47.100
Playhouse and Seattle Rep.

00:10:47.100 --> 00:10:49.380
We took it to Washington,
D.C. We took it back

00:10:49.380 --> 00:10:51.360
to Gander for two
benefit concerts,

00:10:51.360 --> 00:10:54.690
where all the proceeds went
back to local charities, which

00:10:54.690 --> 00:10:57.240
was our way of giving back
to the community there.

00:10:57.240 --> 00:10:59.910
And then took it to Toronto
for a full production,

00:10:59.910 --> 00:11:01.230
and now we're here on Broadway.

00:11:01.230 --> 00:11:01.900
ALAN SEALES: Wow.

00:11:01.900 --> 00:11:03.870
KELLY DEVINE: We've been
on tour for a long time.

00:11:03.870 --> 00:11:05.286
ALAN SEALES: So I
was going to ask

00:11:05.286 --> 00:11:07.640
Kelly and Ian, the two of
you, how did you get attached

00:11:07.640 --> 00:11:09.610
to the show in the first place?

00:11:09.610 --> 00:11:11.065
KELLY DEVINE: Uh,
musical genius.

00:11:14.460 --> 00:11:17.370
IAN EISENDRATH: I was working at
the Fifth Avenue Theater, which

00:11:17.370 --> 00:11:21.420
is a theater in Seattle that
does a lot of development

00:11:21.420 --> 00:11:22.470
of new musicals.

00:11:22.470 --> 00:11:26.010
And at that point, I
met David and Irene.

00:11:26.010 --> 00:11:28.087
And we had a waffle
breakfast that

00:11:28.087 --> 00:11:29.670
was the beginning
of our relationship.

00:11:29.670 --> 00:11:30.490
It was fantastic.

00:11:30.490 --> 00:11:32.281
We decided we could
eat breakfast together,

00:11:32.281 --> 00:11:34.410
we could certainly
make music together.

00:11:34.410 --> 00:11:37.440
And that was in advance
of the workshop.

00:11:37.440 --> 00:11:40.050
That was when Kelly first worked
on the material, and Chris

00:11:40.050 --> 00:11:41.120
Ashley, our director.

00:11:41.120 --> 00:11:45.150
And they've been stuck
with me ever since.

00:11:45.150 --> 00:11:48.120
KELLY DEVINE: I actually
saw their workshop

00:11:48.120 --> 00:11:50.474
that they did in Goodspeed,
is when we first met.

00:11:50.474 --> 00:11:52.640
I was working on another
show and we were neighbors.

00:11:52.640 --> 00:11:54.306
Our houses were next
door to each other,

00:11:54.306 --> 00:11:56.310
because you all sort of
live, all the writers

00:11:56.310 --> 00:11:58.264
and collaborators
who live in a home

00:11:58.264 --> 00:12:00.430
together for two weeks,
which is really interesting.

00:12:00.430 --> 00:12:03.061
And so we'd see each other--

00:12:03.061 --> 00:12:05.560
well, all of a sudden, you feel
like you're at camp together

00:12:05.560 --> 00:12:07.410
with people you don't
know that well, but you're

00:12:07.410 --> 00:12:09.420
like waking up in your
pajamas and you're like,

00:12:09.420 --> 00:12:10.586
I'm going to brush my teeth.

00:12:10.586 --> 00:12:12.110
It's just-- it's all-inclusive.

00:12:12.110 --> 00:12:14.400
Yeah.

00:12:14.400 --> 00:12:16.230
But yeah, so I saw
the show there.

00:12:16.230 --> 00:12:17.730
And then I knew--

00:12:17.730 --> 00:12:19.230
I thought the show
was very special,

00:12:19.230 --> 00:12:22.560
and I particularly think these
two are really, really special.

00:12:22.560 --> 00:12:24.160
We had a lot of fun.

00:12:24.160 --> 00:12:25.975
And then Chris Ashley
called me, and I

00:12:25.975 --> 00:12:27.329
had worked with him prior.

00:12:27.329 --> 00:12:29.370
And he said, hey, I'm
working on this show called

00:12:29.370 --> 00:12:30.078
"Come From Away."

00:12:30.078 --> 00:12:32.040
And I was like, I
know "Come From Away."

00:12:32.040 --> 00:12:33.660
I was so thrilled.

00:12:33.660 --> 00:12:35.190
So yeah, that's
how that happened.

00:12:35.190 --> 00:12:39.540
ALAN SEALES: So you're
the musical staging,

00:12:39.540 --> 00:12:42.240
which isn't-- is that
different from choreographer?

00:12:42.240 --> 00:12:42.900
KELLY DEVINE: You
know, it's funny.

00:12:42.900 --> 00:12:44.330
That question comes up a lot.

00:12:44.330 --> 00:12:45.840
It is and it isn't.

00:12:45.840 --> 00:12:49.320
I mean, any sort of
musical staging to music

00:12:49.320 --> 00:12:50.940
has choreography in it.

00:12:50.940 --> 00:12:53.790
And I think the misconception
is that choreography is just

00:12:53.790 --> 00:12:57.090
dance, like real dance,
like classical dance

00:12:57.090 --> 00:13:00.120
that we're used to seeing in
like "West Side Story" would

00:13:00.120 --> 00:13:02.160
feel like a big dance show.

00:13:02.160 --> 00:13:06.030
And I think choreography
over the last 10 years

00:13:06.030 --> 00:13:08.040
has changed into something else.

00:13:08.040 --> 00:13:10.860
And a lot of time,
moving furniture

00:13:10.860 --> 00:13:14.880
can be just as much choreography
as it is doing a triple turn.

00:13:14.880 --> 00:13:18.930
And I think there's
a little bit of both.

00:13:18.930 --> 00:13:20.700
They're really stoked
about the furniture.

00:13:20.700 --> 00:13:22.020
They're really happy about it.

00:13:22.020 --> 00:13:23.645
SPEAKER 1: None of
us can really dance.

00:13:23.645 --> 00:13:24.614
That's why we laugh.

00:13:24.614 --> 00:13:26.280
KELLY DEVINE: Now,
but you just blew it,

00:13:26.280 --> 00:13:28.530
because everybody thinks you
dance beautifully in the show.

00:13:28.530 --> 00:13:28.980
SPEAKER 1: That's you.

00:13:28.980 --> 00:13:29.790
KELLY DEVINE: I get that a lot.

00:13:29.790 --> 00:13:30.873
SPEAKER 1: That's all you.

00:13:30.873 --> 00:13:33.270
KELLY DEVINE: Well, listen,
we worked on it together.

00:13:33.270 --> 00:13:34.830
But yeah, there is
dance in the show,

00:13:34.830 --> 00:13:38.370
