of moving furniture

00:15:21.440 --> 00:15:22.970
that is choreographed there.

00:15:22.970 --> 00:15:26.070
And it's this magic trick
that we never get tired of.

00:15:26.070 --> 00:15:28.070
It's immediately a bus,
immediately an airplane,

00:15:28.070 --> 00:15:29.990
immediately a legion hall.

00:15:29.990 --> 00:15:32.310
And characters are
switching on a dime.

00:15:32.310 --> 00:15:34.370
It's really-- it's
fun for us to watch,

00:15:34.370 --> 00:15:35.930
and we've seen it
a million times.

00:15:35.930 --> 00:15:37.627
ALAN SEALES: Yeah, I enjoyed it.

00:15:37.627 --> 00:15:39.710
Now that you mention it
again, it's very seamless.

00:15:39.710 --> 00:15:42.050
And you go cut back
and you're creating--

00:15:42.050 --> 00:15:44.790
you're creating individual
scenes without ever changing

00:15:44.790 --> 00:15:45.290
the set.

00:15:45.290 --> 00:15:46.950
I mean, the set itself is fixed.

00:15:46.950 --> 00:15:52.400
It's a one act set on
Broadway, which is very rare.

00:15:52.400 --> 00:15:56.960
But I want to get Ian.

00:15:56.960 --> 00:15:59.180
I'm confused about
musical supervisor,

00:15:59.180 --> 00:16:01.440
or musical arrangements,
but then David and Irene,

00:16:01.440 --> 00:16:04.060
you both are credited
with the music, as well.

00:16:04.060 --> 00:16:07.600
So how did the music
collaboration happen,

00:16:07.600 --> 00:16:09.219
and how did these credits work?

00:16:09.219 --> 00:16:11.510
IAN EISENDRATH: You know,
it's confusing for every show

00:16:11.510 --> 00:16:14.060
and every music department,
but Dave and Irene definitely,

00:16:14.060 --> 00:16:15.590
they wrote the show.

00:16:15.590 --> 00:16:17.420
They created the story.

00:16:17.420 --> 00:16:21.350
They decided who would sing
when and what they would sing.

00:16:21.350 --> 00:16:23.900
And I always think of my
job as the arranger or music

00:16:23.900 --> 00:16:27.910
supervisor to get in
the trenches with them,

00:16:27.910 --> 00:16:33.410
help to flesh out
specific moments based

00:16:33.410 --> 00:16:35.570
on the work that
Kelly's doing, based

00:16:35.570 --> 00:16:38.840
on what Chris is doing,
taking the words and the music

00:16:38.840 --> 00:16:42.020
that they wrote, adding
even more texture,

00:16:42.020 --> 00:16:45.470
putting things in the right
keys for various singers,

00:16:45.470 --> 00:16:47.660
various moments, sometimes
extending things,

00:16:47.660 --> 00:16:49.030
shortening things.

00:16:49.030 --> 00:16:53.060
We have a group of 12
phenomenal actor-singers,

00:16:53.060 --> 00:16:56.990
it's not your traditional
group of even spread of voices.

00:16:56.990 --> 00:16:59.480
It's very much a unique
group of singers,

00:16:59.480 --> 00:17:02.120
and I think we had a great
time in the room figuring out

00:17:02.120 --> 00:17:04.280
what the vocal arrangements
are, like which

00:17:04.280 --> 00:17:07.040
notes each person sings,
and really creating

00:17:07.040 --> 00:17:08.839
a score that lives on them.

00:17:08.839 --> 00:17:11.690
So I'd say Dave and Irene came
to us with like the ground

00:17:11.690 --> 00:17:13.040
plans, the foundation.

00:17:13.040 --> 00:17:15.740
And then our job, sort of
alongside with Chris and Kelly,

00:17:15.740 --> 00:17:17.810
just like they
put it on stage, I

00:17:17.810 --> 00:17:20.900
focused on coloring
in and filling out

00:17:20.900 --> 00:17:23.510
what was already there, which
was just a great baseline

00:17:23.510 --> 00:17:24.464
to build from.

00:17:24.464 --> 00:17:26.630
And working really closely
with this group of people

00:17:26.630 --> 00:17:28.970
and figuring out where did
they live, what notes do they

00:17:28.970 --> 00:17:30.140
sing the best?

00:17:30.140 --> 00:17:32.289
Stylistically, what
do they do the best?

00:17:32.289 --> 00:17:34.580
I think something that's
really special about that show

00:17:34.580 --> 00:17:36.530
and I'll be forever
grateful to-- these

00:17:36.530 --> 00:17:40.820
are like 12 principal actors
who should all be singing solos

00:17:40.820 --> 00:17:42.680
nonstop on a Broadway stage.

00:17:42.680 --> 00:17:45.890
What makes this show unique is
you have these 12 people coming

00:17:45.890 --> 00:17:49.790
together to form an ensemble,
very representative of what

00:17:49.790 --> 00:17:52.940
happened in Newfoundland on that
day, all these people coming

00:17:52.940 --> 00:17:54.390
from all over the world.

00:17:54.390 --> 00:17:56.030
And they are singing
together and we

00:17:56.030 --> 00:18:00.890
are feeling that power of
12 really strong performers

00:18:00.890 --> 00:18:06.430
becoming one and sometimes
representing 15,000.

00:18:06.430 --> 00:18:09.390
DAVID HEIN: And then and
then beyond just the vocals,

00:18:09.390 --> 00:18:11.480
the music of the
show, the band--

00:18:11.480 --> 00:18:14.060
Ian leads our
amazing band onstage,

00:18:14.060 --> 00:18:15.760
which represents
Newfoundland music.

00:18:15.760 --> 00:18:17.330
I grew up on that, and--

00:18:17.330 --> 00:18:18.415
IAN EISENDRATH: you can
get a bodhran in there.

00:18:18.415 --> 00:18:19.030
Yeah, we do.

00:18:20.095 --> 00:18:23.790
Bodhran, fiddles,
accordions, bouzouki--

00:18:23.790 --> 00:18:27.590
IAN EISENDRATH: A guy that plays
over 22 different tin whistles,

00:18:27.590 --> 00:18:29.639
Irish flute, and pipes.

00:18:29.639 --> 00:18:30.680
DAVID HEIN: It's really--

00:18:30.680 --> 00:18:32.720
it's this traditional
authentic music,

00:18:32.720 --> 00:18:35.450
but you put it on
a Broadway stage

00:18:35.450 --> 00:18:40.190
and it feels unique and new,
and we've seen a lot of shows

00:18:40.190 --> 00:18:42.830
and we've never seen
something like this before.

00:18:42.830 --> 00:18:46.370
And then we layer on top of
that world music on top of it,

00:18:46.370 --> 00:18:49.190
to sort of create this
musical metaphor of people

00:18:49.190 --> 00:18:53.000
coming from all over the place
and contrasting, you know,

00:18:53.000 --> 00:18:55.280
fiddles from Newfoundland
versus fiddles from Texas

00:18:55.280 --> 00:18:58.640
or hand drums, bodhrans from
Newfoundland versus hand drums

00:18:58.640 --> 00:19:00.920
from Africa, and
creating something that's

00:19:00.920 --> 00:19:04.850
this layered metaphor for being
stronger together and coming

00:19:04.850 --> 00:19:05.350
together.

00:19:05.350 --> 00:19:08.180
And Ian's been responsible
for the arrangements of that

00:19:08.180 --> 00:19:11.491
and leading it and learning how
to play button accordion, as

00:19:11.491 --> 00:19:11.990
well.

