easy we're with counting in,

00:22:21.072 --> 00:22:23.530
or if they were like, oh me,
or what, you know what I mean?

00:22:23.530 --> 00:22:26.189
Like, it just--
that told me a lot.

00:22:26.189 --> 00:22:27.980
I don't know about you
guys, but because we

00:22:27.980 --> 00:22:29.320
were kind of like in
the dark a little bit,

00:22:29.320 --> 00:22:31.150
being like we don't
really know what we need,

00:22:31.150 --> 00:22:33.441
we kind of know how many we
need, we kind of know ages,

00:22:33.441 --> 00:22:35.730
but that can switch.

00:22:35.730 --> 00:22:37.630
So there was nothing
really solid,

00:22:37.630 --> 00:22:41.110
except for a sense of
being willing to play

00:22:41.110 --> 00:22:50.900
and a sense of sort of a
selflessness, like an openness.

00:22:50.900 --> 00:22:51.400
I mean--

00:22:51.400 --> 00:22:52.630
IAN EISENDRATH: We knew we
were forming an ensemble.

00:22:52.630 --> 00:22:55.690
It's important to find a
group of really strong actors

00:22:55.690 --> 00:22:58.610
that we knew would be willing
to play well together.

00:22:58.610 --> 00:23:00.026
KELLY DEVINE: And
then the essence

00:23:00.026 --> 00:23:02.140
of some of the characters,
of the real life people

00:23:02.140 --> 00:23:04.587
that would find the
story too, I think--

00:23:04.587 --> 00:23:06.670
not that they had to be a
doppelganger or anything

00:23:06.670 --> 00:23:09.790
like that, but just the
essence of who that person is

00:23:09.790 --> 00:23:12.615
and be able to sort of
embrace that and embody it.

00:23:12.615 --> 00:23:14.740
DAVID HEIN: And that's and
that's tricky sometimes,

00:23:14.740 --> 00:23:16.570
because all of the
characters on stage

00:23:16.570 --> 00:23:18.460
are amalgamations
and composites.

00:23:18.460 --> 00:23:20.710
To tell that many stories
in such a short a time,

00:23:20.710 --> 00:23:23.287
we've had to sort of
compress these stories,

00:23:23.287 --> 00:23:24.370
