00:38:49.760 --> 00:38:51.210
She's thankful for it.

00:38:51.210 --> 00:38:52.020
ALAN SEALES: OK.

00:38:52.020 --> 00:38:52.520
Question?

00:38:53.491 --> 00:38:55.366
AUDIENCE: My name's
Ashley, and I've actually

00:38:55.366 --> 00:38:56.060
already seen the show.

00:38:56.060 --> 00:38:57.663
Loved it, can't stop
talking about it.

00:38:57.663 --> 00:38:59.550
I already have tickets
to see it again.

00:38:59.550 --> 00:39:01.020
I think you're all fabulous.

00:39:01.020 --> 00:39:04.690
So I was sitting here trying to
think of what I would ask you,

00:39:04.690 --> 00:39:07.940
and I keep going back to exactly
how much toilet paper did

00:39:07.940 --> 00:39:09.992
they bring to the Lion's Club?

00:39:09.992 --> 00:39:11.450
IRENE SANKOFF: I
think the quote we

00:39:11.450 --> 00:39:14.901
got was enough to last a
year for Gander Academy.

00:39:14.901 --> 00:39:16.400
It was actually, I
want to say-- no,

00:39:16.400 --> 00:39:17.690
where did they drop
it off in real life?

00:39:17.690 --> 00:39:19.160
Because I know we
switch things around,

00:39:19.160 --> 00:39:21.060
because it's not a documentary,
it's a piece of theater.

00:39:21.060 --> 00:39:22.230
So we tried to
amalgamate, think about--

00:39:22.230 --> 00:39:23.090
DAVID HEIN: This
is the Lion's Club.

00:39:23.090 --> 00:39:23.970
IRENE SANKOFF: This
is the Lion's club.

00:39:23.970 --> 00:39:24.830
Yes.

00:39:24.830 --> 00:39:27.320
KELLY DEVINE: So Janice, you
should explain that line,

00:39:27.320 --> 00:39:28.550
just so you get a
little background.

00:39:28.550 --> 00:39:29.550
KENDRA KASSEBAUM: Right.

00:39:29.550 --> 00:39:32.150
So I play a reporter whose it's
the first day on the job when

00:39:32.150 --> 00:39:33.540
all of this is happening.

00:39:33.540 --> 00:39:36.170
And so her job was to kind of
get the information out there,

00:39:36.170 --> 00:39:37.650
what people need and everything.

00:39:37.650 --> 00:39:41.270
And she just put out there that
I we just need a little toilet

00:39:41.270 --> 00:39:43.685
paper over at the Lions
Club, if you got any extra.

00:39:43.685 --> 00:39:46.610
And so she's back on the air
saying for the love of God,

00:39:46.610 --> 00:39:49.520
stop bringing toilet
paper to the Lions Club.

00:39:49.520 --> 00:39:52.160
So that's where that comes from.

00:39:52.160 --> 00:39:55.072
DAVID HEIN: And it
really happened.

00:39:55.072 --> 00:39:55.988
Yes.

00:39:55.988 --> 00:39:58.760
AUDIENCE: Hey, I'm
Joanna, and I'm Canadian,

00:39:58.760 --> 00:40:01.985
so I'm so excited to see
a story about Canada,

00:40:01.985 --> 00:40:04.130
but also curious about
how you opened in Toronto

00:40:04.130 --> 00:40:06.038
and how you got your
start in Toronto

00:40:06.038 --> 00:40:08.659
and then came to New York,
because that feels almost

00:40:08.659 --> 00:40:10.950
like the opposite of shows
usually opening broadly here

00:40:10.950 --> 00:40:12.490
and then going on the road.

00:40:12.490 --> 00:40:13.365
IRENE SANKOFF: It is.

00:40:13.365 --> 00:40:14.690
It is, actually, yeah.

00:40:14.690 --> 00:40:17.700
DAVID HEIN: So we started
at Sheridan College,

00:40:17.700 --> 00:40:21.440
with something called the
Canadian Music Theater Project.

00:40:21.440 --> 00:40:24.260
So all of these
experienced actors

00:40:24.260 --> 00:40:26.840
are having to play characters
that were originally

00:40:26.840 --> 00:40:28.220
based on students.

00:40:28.220 --> 00:40:31.970
We worked with students there,
and also at Goodspeed Musicals.

00:40:31.970 --> 00:40:33.614
And students have
a lot of energy,

00:40:33.614 --> 00:40:35.030
and they jump from
thing to thing,

00:40:35.030 --> 00:40:36.160
and they're happy
to move chairs.

00:40:36.160 --> 00:40:38.240
And so these guys have to
put up with a show that

00:40:38.240 --> 00:40:40.370
was based on that.

00:40:40.370 --> 00:40:42.590
I think what we've
learned along the way

00:40:42.590 --> 00:40:49.170
is that as Canadians
ourselves, it's definitely

00:40:49.170 --> 00:40:52.010
this wonderful Canadian story
that we feel a lot of pride in.

00:40:52.010 --> 00:40:54.770
There was 200 planes
diverted across the country,

00:40:54.770 --> 00:41:00.725
not only to Gander but also
out on the west coast and all

00:41:00.725 --> 00:41:01.350
over the place.

00:41:01.350 --> 00:41:04.700
But it's also, as
New Yorkers, it's

00:41:04.700 --> 00:41:06.590
people who are here
in New York, there's

00:41:06.590 --> 00:41:09.650
this sense that it's an
American story, as well.

00:41:09.650 --> 00:41:14.280
It's an additional memory
to what happened on 9/11.

00:41:14.280 --> 00:41:18.050
And everyone we've talked
to, Hannah's family,

00:41:18.050 --> 00:41:20.480
but also when we're
in Washington, D.C.,

00:41:20.480 --> 00:41:21.914
we spoke to a lot
of the survivors

00:41:21.914 --> 00:41:23.330
and the survivors'
families there.

00:41:23.330 --> 00:41:26.120
We've talked to--
our first preview was

00:41:26.120 --> 00:41:28.060
for the FDNY Foundation here.

00:41:28.060 --> 00:41:31.100
And what they told us was
that what happened in Gander

00:41:31.100 --> 00:41:34.160
was a tribute to the people
that they lost, that it was not

00:41:34.160 --> 00:41:37.130
a replacement memory, but an
additional memory and a glimmer

00:41:37.130 --> 00:41:40.460
of hope on such a tragic day.

00:41:40.460 --> 00:41:42.260
So I think it's
important for them.

00:41:42.260 --> 00:41:44.090
And beyond that,
what we've realized

00:41:44.090 --> 00:41:45.940
is that it's really an
international story.

00:41:45.940 --> 00:41:50.210
It was something that happened
to the world at the same time,

00:41:50.210 --> 00:41:53.390
and that we all had reactions
to it, wherever you were from.

00:41:53.390 --> 00:41:57.487
And that sort of coalesced
for us in the story of Gander,

00:41:57.487 --> 00:41:59.570
because so many people
were from around the world.

00:41:59.570 --> 00:42:02.000
So it expanded beyond there.

00:42:02.000 --> 00:42:06.050
We've also had an
amazing team who's

00:42:06.050 --> 00:42:08.330
supported the show, this
little Canadian show

00:42:08.330 --> 00:42:10.262
and has brought it to the world.

00:42:10.262 --> 00:42:11.720
And we've been
really blessed to be

00:42:11.720 --> 00:42:13.860
able to share this with as
many people as possible.

00:42:13.860 --> 00:42:16.696
We have a team that
I think originally

00:42:16.696 --> 00:42:18.320
wasn't sure whether
this was a Broadway

00:42:18.320 --> 00:42:20.840
show but knew that it was
an important story to tell

00:42:20.840 --> 00:42:22.610
and has supported it
all along the way.

00:42:22.610 --> 00:42:24.110
IAN EISENDRATH: And
one of the gifts

00:42:24.110 --> 00:42:26.660
that I think our producers
gave us, often shows

00:42:26.660 --> 00:42:30.170
are go as quickly as
possible to get to New York.

00:42:30.170 --> 00:42:33.950
They gave us the gift of time
and multiple productions,

00:42:33.950 --> 00:42:35.960
and we didn't just
rush to New York.

00:42:35.960 --> 00:42:38.600
The goal was not just
to have a Broadway show,

00:42:38.600 --> 00:42:41.660
but to really explore
the story and tell it

00:42:41.660 --> 00:42:44.570
in the most truthful,
honoring, and effective way.

00:42:44.570 --> 00:42:47.450
And I think playing
Canada, playing La Jolla,

00:42:47.450 --> 00:42:50.780
playing Seattle, playing
D.C., which was directly

00:42:50.780 --> 00:42:53.450
impacted by 9/11, all
these different cities

00:42:53.450 --> 00:42:57.830
and listening to those
audiences helped all of us

00:42:57.830 --> 00:43:00.410
hone everything, from the
writing to the staging

00:43:00.410 --> 00:43:02.510
to the music to the production.

00:43:02.510 --> 00:43:04.910
RODNEY HICKS: And it
gave us a real journey,

00:43:04.910 --> 00:43:10.360
a familial journey of coming
together amongst ourselves

00:43:10.360 --> 00:43:12.700
and this bond that we have.

00:43:15.890 --> 00:43:17.390
ALAN SEALES: So
other than the rent,

00:43:17.390 --> 00:43:18.806
did anything change
about the show

00:43:18.806 --> 00:43:21.429
going from Toronto to New York?

00:43:21.429 --> 00:43:22.220
IRENE SANKOFF: Yes.

00:43:22.220 --> 00:43:22.820
KELLY DEVINE: Yeah.

00:43:22.820 --> 00:43:23.380
Yeah, a lot.

00:43:23.380 --> 00:43:24.860
IRENE SANKOFF: We
added a new song.

00:43:24.860 --> 00:43:25.230
ALAN SEALES: Did you?

00:43:25.230 --> 00:43:25.510
IRENE SANKOFF: Yes.

00:43:25.510 --> 00:43:26.593
ALAN SEALES: What was new?

00:43:26.593 --> 00:43:27.910
IRENE SANKOFF: Hannah's song.

00:43:27.910 --> 00:43:28.340
ALAN SEALES: Oh, nice.

00:43:28.340 --> 00:43:28.610
Yeah.

00:43:28.610 --> 00:43:29.000
That song is new.

00:43:29.000 --> 00:43:29.960
IRENE SANKOFF: Expanded.

00:43:29.960 --> 00:43:32.209
DAVID HEIN: We continued to
tweak and tighten and cut.

00:43:32.209 --> 00:43:34.460
You know, it's funny.

00:43:34.460 --> 00:43:37.790
Working with the same
team over so many cities

00:43:37.790 --> 00:43:40.820
within the theater,
it felt very safe.

00:43:40.820 --> 00:43:42.410
We were all just
doing what we do.

00:43:42.410 --> 00:43:45.200
We were just making the show
as good as we possibly could.

00:43:45.200 --> 00:43:47.450
It was only when you go out
the door that you're like,

00:43:47.450 --> 00:43:48.491
oh my god, it's Broadway.

00:43:48.491 --> 00:43:49.465
What's--

00:43:49.465 --> 00:43:51.590
IAN EISENDRATH: Well, I
feel like one of the things

00:43:51.590 --> 00:43:53.617
that changed with the
show is that you guys kept

00:43:53.617 --> 00:43:55.700
interviewing people, and
they kept meeting people.

00:43:55.700 --> 00:43:56.930
That's why we got a new song.

00:43:56.930 --> 00:43:59.750
And it's such a credit
to them as writers.

00:43:59.750 --> 00:44:01.784
They could have made
up phenomenal stories.

00:44:01.784 --> 00:44:03.700
They were so committed
to capturing the truth.

00:44:03.700 --> 00:44:07.400
And once they spent a good
amount of time with Hannah,

00:44:07.400 --> 00:44:10.195
suddenly a song flowed out
of them and we have that.

00:44:10.195 --> 00:44:12.110
So it's been an
interesting process.

00:44:12.110 --> 00:44:13.485
KELLY DEVINE: I
have to add, too,

00:44:13.485 --> 00:44:16.070
that our director, Chris
Ashley pushed all of us

00:44:16.070 --> 00:44:17.279
at every moment relentlessly.

00:44:17.279 --> 00:44:18.445
IRENE SANKOFF: Relentlessly.

00:44:18.445 --> 00:44:19.700
KELLY DEVINE: Never stopped.

00:44:19.700 --> 00:44:22.149
To the very last second
before we opened.

00:44:22.149 --> 00:44:24.732
DAVID HEIN: I think last night
I actually got a note via text.

00:44:24.732 --> 00:44:26.523
IRENE SANKOFF: I blocked
his email address.

00:44:30.582 --> 00:44:32.540
KELLY DEVINE: He really
had such a good insight

00:44:32.540 --> 00:44:34.164
to what you guys
wanted, and he sort of

00:44:34.164 --> 00:44:35.280
set us on the right path.

00:44:35.280 --> 00:44:38.240
And then he just wouldn't
accept anything that

00:44:38.240 --> 00:44:39.860
was just slightly undercooked.

00:44:39.860 --> 00:44:43.550
Sometimes when you're
really on a tight schedule

00:44:43.550 --> 00:44:45.710
and you got to open
something, it's easy to go,

00:44:45.710 --> 00:44:47.180
you know what, that's fine.

00:44:47.180 --> 00:44:49.040
Let's keep going, it's working.

00:44:49.040 --> 00:44:50.870
But that wasn't ever acceptable.

00:44:50.870 --> 00:44:52.910
We always had to
go deeper, which

00:44:52.910 --> 00:44:58.190
I think is why we are
up here, because I think

00:44:58.190 --> 00:45:00.470
we've done something
that we're proud of,

00:45:00.470 --> 00:45:03.784
that we took a long,
long time to cultivate.

00:45:03.784 --> 00:45:05.450
ALAN SEALES: All
right, to wrap up here,

00:45:05.450 --> 00:45:07.492
after people see
the show, what's

00:45:07.492 --> 00:45:09.950
the one thing that you hope
people take away with them when

00:45:09.950 --> 00:45:12.400
they leave?

00:45:12.400 --> 00:45:14.720
DAVID HEIN: There's
a Mr. Rogers quote

00:45:14.720 --> 00:45:16.460
that we like to
talk about, which

00:45:16.460 --> 00:45:20.780
is that when his mom said when
he saw something scary on TV,

00:45:20.780 --> 00:45:23.870
his mother used to tell him,
if you see something scary,

00:45:23.870 --> 00:45:25.700
always look for the helpers.

00:45:25.700 --> 00:45:28.070
There's always
goodness in the world.

00:45:28.070 --> 00:45:30.830
There's always-- and
that doesn't often

00:45:30.830 --> 00:45:31.770
doesn't get the focus.

00:45:31.770 --> 00:45:35.070
And it feels
particularly right now

00:45:35.070 --> 00:45:39.970
when we're often feeling
divided against each other,

00:45:39.970 --> 00:45:42.650
it's important to look for
stories that bring us together,

00:45:42.650 --> 00:45:45.332
to focus on the people
who are helping.

00:45:45.332 --> 00:45:47.540
There's always more helpers
than there are people who

00:45:47.540 --> 00:45:49.760
are perpetrating these acts.

00:45:49.760 --> 00:45:56.390
And it feels important to stick
it in your search bar every day

00:45:56.390 --> 00:45:59.780
and find those things that
remind us that there's

00:45:59.780 --> 00:46:02.120
goodness in the world.

00:46:02.120 --> 00:46:03.615
That's what I keep
coming back to.

00:46:03.615 --> 00:46:04.770
ALAN SEALES: Nice.

00:46:04.770 --> 00:46:06.860
IRENE SANKOFF: Yeah, I
think about at the end

00:46:06.860 --> 00:46:08.870
of the year, last
year, 2016, there

00:46:08.870 --> 00:46:12.020
was that video that was put
together because everyone

00:46:12.020 --> 00:46:13.580
was like, see you later, 2016.

00:46:13.580 --> 00:46:14.780
But there was like oh, but--

00:46:14.780 --> 00:46:16.821
like you go through this
thing where it was like,

00:46:16.821 --> 00:46:21.150
PS, but this happened in 2016,
and we accomplished this.

00:46:21.150 --> 00:46:22.127
And it just sort of--

00:46:22.127 --> 00:46:24.710
I mean, it sounds really trite
to say look on the bright side,

00:46:24.710 --> 00:46:25.340
but it's not.

00:46:25.340 --> 00:46:29.720
It's more where you choose to
put your energy and your focus,

00:46:29.720 --> 00:46:31.370
and I think that
does affect what

00:46:31.370 --> 00:46:32.540
you put out into the world.

00:46:32.540 --> 00:46:33.260
I do.

00:46:33.260 --> 00:46:37.400
And so it's much the same thing.

00:46:37.400 --> 00:46:39.890
DAVID HEIN: Yeah, it's been
good for us to tell the story

00:46:39.890 --> 00:46:41.265
and be able to
live in the story.

00:46:41.265 --> 00:46:45.410
I think it's been good for
all of us to be celebrating

00:46:45.410 --> 00:46:47.617
these people out of
Newfoundland, to be celebrating

00:46:47.617 --> 00:46:49.700
the goodness that they
created and the friendships

00:46:49.700 --> 00:46:50.450
that they created.

00:46:50.450 --> 00:46:53.210
It feels like every
day we're living

00:46:53.210 --> 00:46:55.730
in the shadow of
something terrible,

00:46:55.730 --> 00:47:01.077
and it feels important to
find the pockets of good.

00:47:01.077 --> 00:47:02.160
IAN EISENDRATH: Well said.

00:47:02.450 --> 00:47:03.950
PETRINA BROMLEY: I
just want to add,

00:47:03.950 --> 00:47:05.960
I'm actually from
Newfoundland myself.

00:47:05.960 --> 00:47:08.340
And as a member of the cast
on a very personal level

00:47:08.340 --> 00:47:11.665
to be involved with this show,
people come to me all the time

00:47:11.665 --> 00:47:14.040
after the show who have come
from Newfoundland to see it.

00:47:14.040 --> 00:47:16.410
And the kind of
pride that happens

00:47:16.410 --> 00:47:18.990
and the smiles and the
pleasure on people's faces

00:47:18.990 --> 00:47:22.470
just gives me an extra
added bonus of joy

00:47:22.470 --> 00:47:26.040
in this show, because
we don't toot our horns

00:47:26.040 --> 00:47:29.210
enough in Canada, and
especially in Newfoundland.

00:47:29.210 --> 00:47:32.970
So for me, I get
that extra joy on top

00:47:32.970 --> 00:47:34.385
of what they're talking about.

